        <div type="letter">
         <opener><dateline><date when="1917-07-14">July 14, 1917.<dateline></date><salute>Dear <persName key="harriet-monroe">Harriet</persName>:</salute>
        </opener>
            <p>I am awfully glad that you are going to take <title key="theLandladyOfWhintonInn" level="a">“The Whinton Inn”</title>. <measure type="currency" num="75">Seventy-five dollars</measure> will do very well, and so will <date when="1917-11">November</date>. If we wait until <date when="1918-01">January</date> it seems a long way off, as my last group of poems came out in March, and I think you usually figure on having me twice a year, so do make it<date when="1917-11">November</date> if you can. I understand I am to head the number <title key="poetry" level="j">it</title> is in — <foreign xml:lang="fr">n’est-ce pas?</foreign></p>
            <!-- Hunt's poem was not specified -->
           <p>I am enclosing <persName key="richard_hunt">Hunt</persName><title>’s poem</title>, which <persName key="james_oppenheim">Oppenheim</persName> has just returned to me. I have read it over again, and I think it one of the most beautiful things I have read for a long time. I congratulate you on having it, and I hope on re-reading it you will commend my judgment.</p>
            <p>I am awfully glad to hear that you are feeling so well. My eyes are a little better, but I cannot leave off my glasses for five minutes without giving a headache, and as I am not used to them, they handicap me dreadfully.</p>
            <closer>Affectionately yours,</closer>
            <!-- This paragraph below is not in the scanned letter but is in the transcripted one -->
           <p>
           <!-- (space for signature) -->
           </p>
           <postscript><label>P.S.</label> We have decided not to go to Dublin this summer.</postscript>
            </p>
